3":"1283","1192":"1192","Whatton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Whatton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Whatton, Nottingham, England":"Whatton, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Whatton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Whatton (Notts), or Long Whatton (Leics)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard de Whatton was born about 1192, in Whatton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Walter III de Whatton Sir. He had at least 1 son with Margaret de Mandeville."},"et":{"about 1192–":"umbes 1192–Surnud","1192–Male":"1192–Surnud","1203–Male":"1203–Surnud","1283–Female":"1283–Surnud","1224–1300":"1224–1300","1158–Male":"1158–Surnud","about 1192":"umbes 1192","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1158":"1158","1300":"1300","1283":"1283","1192":"1192","Whatton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Whatton, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whatton, Nottingham, England":"Whatton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1192–":"noin 1192–Kuollut","1192–Male":"1192–Kuollut","1203–Male":"1203–Kuollut","1283–Female":"1283–Kuollut","1224–1300":"1224–1300","1158–Male":"1158–Kuollut","about 1192":"noin 1192","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1158":"1158","1300":"1300","1283":"1283","1192":"1192","Whatton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Whatton, Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Whatton, Nottingham, England":"Whatton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1192–":"environ 1192–Décédé","1192–Male":"1192–Décédé","1203–Male":"1203–Décédé","1283–Female":"1283–Décédée","1224–1300":"1224–1300","1158–Male":"1158–Décédé","about 1192":"enviro